    "output": "To convert a stereo audio file to mono while avoiding clipping, you should first mix the two channels down to one by averaging them. Simply summing stereo channels can cause peaks to increase and result in clipping. Using the `pan` audio filter in ffmpeg to average the left and right channels ensures the output stays within proper amplitude limits.\n\n- `pan=mono|c0=0.5*c0+0.5*c1` creates a mono channel by averaging left (c0) and right (c1) at half volume each.\n- To further prevent clipping, you can optionally apply a limiter or volume normalization filter, but the averaging pan filter is typically sufficient for stereo to mono.\n\nHereâ€™s a command example assuming the input is `input.wav` and output is `output_mono.wav`:\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i input.wav -af \"pan=mono|c0=0.5*c0+0.5*c1\" -c:a pcm_s16le output_mono.wav\n```\n\nExplanation:\n- `-af` applies the audio filter.\n- `pcm_s16le` is common uncompressed WAV audio codec; adjust codec as needed.\n- Adjust volume or apply normalization afterward if needed to ensure no clipping. For most stereo-to-mono mixes, this pan operation safely avoids clipping.",
